*************************** T H E O R Y **************************8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
TALYS is a computer code system for the prediction and analysis   8225 1451
of nuclear reactions. TALYS simulates reactions that involve      8225 1451
neutrons, gamma-rays, protons, deuterons, tritons, helions and    8225 1451
alpha-particles, in the 1 keV - 200 MeV energy range and for      8225 1451
target nuclides of mass 12 and heavier. This is achieved by       8225 1451
implementing a suite of nuclear reaction models into a single     8225 1451
code system. It enables to evaluate nuclear reactions from        8225 1451
the unresolved resonance region up to intermediate energies. This 8225 1451
evaluation is based on a theoretical analysis that utilizes the   8225 1451
optical model, compound nucleus statistical theory, direct        8225 1451
reactions and pre-equilibrium processes, in combination with      8225 1451
databases and models for nuclear structure. For Pb-204, the       8225 1451
following output of TALYS is stored in this data file:            8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
- Total, elastic and non-elastic cross sections                   8225 1451
- Elastic scattering angular distributions                        8225 1451
- Inelastic cross sections to discrete states                     8225 1451
- Inelastic scattering angular distributions to discrete states   8225 1451
- Exclusive channel cross sections, e.g. (n,g), (n,2n), (n,np),.. 8225 1451
- Exclusive channel energy spectra                                8225 1451
- Exclusive channel double-differential spectra                   8225 1451
- Exclusive gamma production for discrete states and continuum    8225 1451
- Isomeric and ground state cross sections                        8225 1451
- Residual production cross sections                              8225 1451
- Total particle cross sections, e.g. (n,xn), (n,xp),..           8225 1451
- Total particle energy spectra                                   8225 1451
- Total particle double-differential spectra                      8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
Here follows a short description of the used nuclear models:      8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
##### OPTICAL MODEL                                               8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
All optical model calculations are performed by ECIS-97 [ray94],  8225 1451
in TALYS used as a subroutine. The default optical model          8225 1451
potentials (OMP) used are the local and global parameterizations  8225 1451
of Koning and Delaroche [kon03]. These are phenomenological OMPs  8225 1451
for neutrons and protons which in principle are valid over the    8225 1451
1 keV - 200 MeV energy range, though the low energy boundary of   8225 1451
validity may differ from nucleus to nucleus (e.g. for the total   8225 1451
cross sections, experimental data are included directly in the    8225 1451
file for energies below that boundary). Solving the Schroedinger  8225 1451
equation with this OMP yields the total cross section, the        8225 1451
shape-elastic cross section, the shape-elastic angular            8225 1451
distribution, the wave functions for the direct reaction cross    8225 1451
sections (see below), the transmission coefficients for the       8225 1451
compound nucleus model (see below) and the reaction cross         8225 1451
sections for the pre-equilibrium model (see below).               8225 1451
For neutrons and protons, the used parameterization is given in   8225 1451
Eq. (7) of [kon03].                                               8225 1451
To calculate the transmission coefficients and reaction cross     8225 1451
sections for deuterons, tritons, helions and alpha particles, we  8225 1451
use OMPs that are directly derived from our nucleon potentials    8225 1451
using Watanabe's folding approach [mad88].                        8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
##### DIRECT REACTIONS                                            8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
The built-in ECIS-97 is used for coupled-channels or DWBA         8225 1451
calculations for rotational or vibrational (or a combination of   8225 1451
these) nuclides. For Pb-204, DWBA was used to compute the direct  8225 1451
cross sections to several low-lying discrete levels:              8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
Level   Energy  Spin/Parity   Deformation parameter beta_L        8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
   1   0.899171   2.0+          0.039                             8225 1451
  44   2.627350   5.0+          0.088                             8225 1451
 + a few additional states with small deformation parameters.     8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
In addition, a macroscopic, phenomenological model to describe    8225 1451
giant resonances in the inelastic channel is used. For each       8225 1451
multipolarity an energy weighted sum rule applies and a DWBA      8225 1451
calculation with ECIS-97 is performed for each giant resonance    8225 1451
state. The cross section is then spread over the continuum with a 8225 1451
Gaussian distribution.                                            8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
##### COMPOUND NUCLEUS                                            8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
For binary compound nucleus reactions we use the model of         8225 1451
Moldauer [mol80], i.e. the Hauser-Feshbach model [hau52]          8225 1451
corrected for width fluctuations. The transmission coefficients   8225 1451
have been generated with the aforementioned OMPs and the full     8225 1451
j,l-dependence of the transmission coefficients in the            8225 1451
Hauser-Feshbach model is used. For each nucleus that can be       8225 1451
reached through a binary reaction, several discrete levels and a  8225 1451
continuum described by level densities are included               8225 1451
simultaneously as competing channels.                             8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
The compound nucleus angular distributions are calculated with    8225 1451
the Blatt-Biedenharn formalism [bla52], leading to compound       8225 1451
nucleus Legendre coefficients that are added to their direct      8225 1451
counterparts. For multiple compound emission, i.e. emitted        8225 1451
particles after the binary emission, we use the Hauser-Feshbach   8225 1451
model. Again, for each residual nucleus several discrete states   8225 1451
are included as well as a continuum described by level densities. 8225 1451
Multiple compound emission is continued until all reaction        8225 1451
channels are closed and the population distribution of all        8225 1451
residual nuclides is depleted, through gamma decay, until they    8225 1451
end up in the ground state or in an isomer.                       8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
For the level density, we take the composite formula proposed by  8225 1451
Gilbert and Cameron [gil65], consisting of a constant temperature 8225 1451
law at low energies and a Fermi gas expression at high energies.  8225 1451
For the level density parameter a we use the energy dependent     8225 1451
expression proposed by Ignatyuk [ign75] to take into account the  8225 1451
damping of shell effects at high excitation energy. We have       8225 1451
obtained the parameters for the Ignatyuk formula from a           8225 1451
simultaneous fit to all experimental D_0 values as present in the 8225 1451
RIPL library. If necessary, we adjust individual parameters to    8225 1451
obtain a better fit to experiment.                                8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
Gamma-ray transmission coefficients are generated with the        8225 1451
Kopecky-Uhl generalized Lorentzian for strength                   8225 1451
functions [kop90], with giant dipole resonance parameters taken   8225 1451
from the RIPL library [rip98], and normalized with experimental   8225 1451
radiative widths [gar84].                                         8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
##### PRE-EQUILIBRIUM REACTIONS                                   8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
For pre-equilibrium reactions, which become important for         8225 1451
incident energies above about 10 MeV, we use the two-component    8225 1451
exciton model [kon04b], in which the neutron or proton types of   8225 1451
particles and holes are followed throughout the reaction. For     8225 1451
energies above 20 MeV, multiple pre-equilibrium emission up to    8225 1451
any order of particle emission was included in the calculations.  8225 1451
A parameterization for the squared matrix element is used that is 8225 1451
valid for the whole energy range of this evaluation.              8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
For deuterons, tritons, helions and alpha-particles, an extra     8225 1451
contribution was added from the pick/up and knock-out reaction    8225 1451
model by Kalbach [kal01].                                         8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
For photons, the model of Akkermans and Gruppelaar [akk85] was    8225 1451
applied, to simulate the direct and semi-direct capture           8225 1451
processes.                                                        8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
The angular distribution systematics by Kalbach [kal88] were used 8225 1451
to describe the angular distributions for all continuum           8225 1451
particles. An isotopic distribution for photons was adopted.      8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
****** C O M P A R I S O N    W I T H    E X P E R I M E N T *****8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
This evaluation was performed simultaneously with other adjacent  8225 1451
isotopes, both for incident neutrons and protons. This enables,   8225 1451
when compared with a single-isotope effort, to put stronger       8225 1451
constraints on the produced calculated data, i.e. a globally      8225 1451
good comparison between TALYS and experimental data is requested  8225 1451
for all isotopes at the same time, while nucleus-specific input   8225 1451
(default or adjusted) parameters are consistently used for all    8225 1451
isotopes. Also, experimental data that is not available for the   8225 1451
isotope under study may be present, and tested, for adjacent      8225 1451
nuclides or for other projectiles. If these can be successfully   8225 1451
described by the models, a similar performance can be expected    8225 1451
for the present data file. Examples are the (p,xn)....(p,xa)      8225 1451
spectra for Pb-208 and Pb-nat and the (n,xn) excitation functions 8225 1451
up to 200 MeV for Bi-209.                                         8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
##### TOTAL AND REACTION CROSS SECTIONS AND ELASTIC SCATTERING    8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
The spherical OMP was tested against experimental data for        8225 1451
natural Pb, in particular the cross section set of [fin93]. The   8225 1451
used parameters are those of Table 10 of [kon03]. Consult         8225 1451
[kon03] for the complete experimental database of elastic         8225 1451
scattering angular distributions and for a comparison of          8225 1451
calculations and measurements over the whole energy range.        8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
##### INELASTIC CROSS SECTIONS                                    8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
Only experimental data for inelastic scattering to the isomeric,  8225 1451
21th, state is available for Pb-204. Various experimental data    8225 1451
sets exist in the EXFOR database, including the recent            8225 1451
measurements of Plompen et al. [plo02]. In order to get better    8225 1451
agreement with the production of this isomer, the spin cutoff     8225 1451
factor has been multiplied by a factor of 1.8. Further,           8225 1451
adjustment of the default matrix element parameterization of      8225 1451
[kon04b] for pre-equilibrium reactions was needed. M**2 was       8225 1451
multiplied by 1.3 to get better agreement with the data.          8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
##### OTHER PARTIAL CROSS SECTIONS                                8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
- (n,gamma):                                                      8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
The calculated capture cross section is renormalized, by          8225 1451
overruling the default renormalization to the s-wave strength     8225 1451
function, to the available experimental data, all taken from the  8225 1451
EXFOR database. A normalization factor of 0.60 was used. The      8225 1451
pre-equilibrium gamma cross section was adjusted to the data by   8225 1451
multiplying the calculated result by a factor of 3.0.             8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
- (n,2n):                                                         8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
The calculated results have been validated with many experimental 8225 1451
(n,2n) cross sections from EXFOR. Recent experiments for the      8225 1451
total as well as isomeric production [plo02] have been taken into 8225 1451
account.  An independent test comes from the description of the   8225 1451
differential energy spectra at 14 MeV [sch97].                    8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
- (n,3n):                                                         8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
Validated with new [plo02] experimental data.                     8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
- (n,p):                                                          8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
New experimental data for (n,p) [plo02] exists around 20 MeV.     8225 1451
TALYS overestimates these cross sections by a factor of 2, which  8225 1451
amounts to 10 mb. We were not able to adjust calculation to these 8225 1451
data.                                                             8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
##### PARTICLE SPECTRA                                            8225 1451
                                                                  8225 1451
For high-energy neutron and charged particle spectra, the average 8225 1451
quality is determined by the pre-equilibrium model and its        8225 1451
global parameterization. Two experiments from the HINDAS project, 8225 1451
for neutron induced reaction spectra at 63 MeV [ker02] and 96 MeV 8225 1451
[lec03], have enabled us to better constrain the results, through 8225 1451
the aforementioned matrix element, for particle yields and        8225 1451
double-differential spectra for all ejectiles up to alpha         8225 1451
particles.                                                        8225 1451
